What Are Intent Signals and Why Do They Matter?
Intent signals are behavioral data points that indicate a person or organization is actively researching a topic, category, or solution. These signals come from a wide range of sources: content consumption on third-party publisher networks, keyword search activity, competitor website visits, engagement with review platforms, webinar registrations, and more.

In practical terms, if a VP of IT at a mid-sized healthcare company in Chicago has spent the past two weeks reading articles about cloud security compliance, downloading white papers on zero-trust architecture, and visiting the websites of three cybersecurity vendors, that is a strong intent signal. That prospect is in-market. They are not a cold lead. They are a warm opportunity.

Intent data has become a foundational element of modern B2B marketing because it removes the guesswork from targeting. Instead of defining your audience by demographics and hoping some of them happen to need your solution right now, intent data lets you identify the accounts that are actively signaling a need. According to industry research, B2B marketers using intent data report significantly higher engagement rates, shorter sales cycles, and improved pipeline quality compared to those using demographic targeting alone.

The two primary categories of intent data worth knowing:
First-party intent data is collected directly from your own digital properties — website visits, content downloads, demo requests, email engagement, and so on. This data is highly accurate because it reflects direct interaction with your brand.

Third-party intent data is collected from across the broader web by data providers who aggregate behavioral signals from publisher networks, research platforms, and other digital environments. This data expands your visibility beyond your own properties and helps you identify in-market buyers before they ever reach your website.

The most effective intent-driven demand generation programs in 2026 combine both types, using first-party data to understand existing engagement and third-party data to identify net-new opportunities.

What Is Geo-Targeted Marketing in a B2B Context?
Geo-targeted marketing is the practice of tailoring your marketing messages, channels, and timing based on the geographic location of your target audience. In B2B, this goes well beyond simply running ads in a specific city. It involves understanding regional industry clusters, local economic conditions, state-specific regulatory environments, and even the competitive dynamics unique to a given metro area.

For a US-focused B2B company, geo-targeting can mean concentrating demand generation efforts on the technology corridors of Austin and San Francisco, the financial services hubs of New York and Chicago, the healthcare systems concentrated in cities like Houston and Boston, or the manufacturing belts of the Midwest. Each of these regions has distinct business cultures, decision-making patterns, and competitive landscapes.

When geo-targeting is applied thoughtfully in B2B, it allows marketers to craft messaging that speaks directly to local context. A campaign targeting cybersecurity buyers in the Washington DC area, where government contracting and compliance requirements dominate the conversation, will look very different from a campaign targeting the same buyer persona in Seattle, where the tech-native culture and startup ecosystem shape different priorities and preferences.

How Intent Signals and Geo-Targeting Work Together
The real power emerges when these two strategies are layered on top of each other. Intent data tells you who is in-market right now. Geo-targeting tells you where they are and how to speak their language. Together, they create a targeting framework that is both timely and contextually relevant.

Here is how this plays out in practice across the demand generation funnel.

At the top of the funnel
AI-powered platforms analyze third-party intent signals to identify accounts that are surging on topics relevant to your solution. When this data is filtered by geography, you can quickly see which metro areas or regions are showing the highest concentration of in-market activity. This allows you to prioritize content syndication, display advertising, and social media campaigns in the areas where buying activity is already elevated, rather than spreading budget evenly across the entire country.

In the middle of the funnel
Once target accounts have been identified through intent and geo data, the next step is running account-based marketing campaigns that combine geographic personalization with intent-informed messaging. This might mean developing landing pages and ad creative that reference regional industry events, local compliance regulations, or challenges specific to that market. It might mean having your SDRs reference a recent development in the prospect's city when initiating outreach. Small signals of local awareness create outsized trust and relevance.

At the bottom of the funnel
Appointment setting programs benefit significantly from geo-aware execution. SDRs who are briefed on the local context of the accounts they are reaching out to have more natural, credible conversations. When outreach is timed around local industry events, regional conferences, or even seasonal business patterns, response rates improve. A prospect in Phoenix who just attended a regional fintech summit and has been actively researching payment processing solutions is a fundamentally different conversation than a cold outbound call made without any of that context.

